    # 16: wp-super-cache is_bot_user_agent
    {
        "instruction": "<wp_gen> Create a WordPress caching plugin class method that detects whether a given user agent string belongs to a known web crawler or bot, using a comprehensive hardcoded list of bot agent substrings with source attribution comments for each vendor's documentation, and using stripos for case-insensitive substring matching with early return on first match.",
        "cot_reasoning": "Step-by-step explanation of the key decisions in this code:\n1. The empty() guard returns false immediately for null or empty user agents. Many programmatic requests send no User-Agent header; treating them as bots would incorrectly skip caching for legitimate API consumers.\n2. stripos() is used instead of strpos() for case-insensitive matching. User-Agent strings from real bots vary in capitalization across versions and platforms, so case-insensitive matching is required for reliable detection.\n3. The bot list is hardcoded rather than stored in the database. For a caching plugin, database reads on every uncached request would be a significant performance penalty; the in-memory array has near-zero overhead.\n4. Source attribution comments (linking to Bing's official crawler documentation, ua-parser project) make the list auditable and maintainable. Future developers can verify entries and add new ones with confidence.\n5. The function returns true on the first match rather than collecting all matching patterns. For a boolean detection function, finding one match is sufficient, and early return minimizes the number of stripos() calls per request.\n6. The $ua parameter has a default of null and is checked with empty() rather than type-checking. This makes the function usable in contexts where the UA may not be available without requiring callers to check first.",
        "training_tags": ["user-agent-detection", "bot-detection", "stripos", "array-iteration", "class-method", "early-return", "input-validation", "caching-optimization"],
        "complexity": "simple",
    },
    # 17: wp-super-cache scossdl_off_get_options
    {
        "instruction": "<wp_gen> Create a WordPress CDN configuration options loader function that reads CDN settings from the database using get_option with strict false comparison, initializes missing options with add_option defaults, resolves the blog URL with untrailingslashit, splits comma-separated CNAME strings into trimmed arrays using array_map and array_filter, and applies a filter hook for extensibility.",
        "cot_reasoning": "Step-by-step explanation of the key decisions in this code:\n1. Global variables are used because this is a legacy procedural plugin. The options are loaded into globals so they are accessible throughout the plugin's function set without passing parameters.\n2. false === get_option() (strict comparison) distinguishes between an option that does not exist (returns false) and one saved as an empty string (returns ''). Using == would treat both as falsy and overwrite intentionally-empty settings.\n3. add_option() (not update_option()) is used for initialization. add_option() is a no-op if the option already exists, making it safe to call on every request without overwriting user configuration.\n4. untrailingslashit(get_site_url()) normalizes the blog URL. CDN URL rewriting requires exact string prefix matching; a trailing slash mismatch would cause rewrites to fail.\n5. array_map('trim', ...) on the comma-separated CNAME list removes whitespace from user-entered values. Users frequently add spaces after commas when entering CDN hostnames.\n6. array_filter() removes empty strings that result from trailing commas in the stored value (e.g., 'cdn1.example.com,'). An empty CNAME in the list would produce malformed CDN URLs.\n7. apply_filters() on the final options array allows advanced users to override CDN settings programmatically, useful for multisite setups where different subsites need different CDN configurations.",
        "training_tags": ["options-api", "global-variables", "apply_filters", "add_option", "get_option", "untrailingslashit", "get_site_url", "array_map", "array_filter", "option-initialization-pattern", "cdn-configuration"],
        "complexity": "simple",
    },
    # 18: wpsc_register_post_hooks
    {
        "instruction": "<wp_gen> Create a WordPress cache invalidation hook registration function that uses a static boolean guard for idempotency, checks global cache_enabled and a WPLOCKDOWN constant before registering, then hooks into post lifecycle actions (publish, trash, edit, delete), comment events, and cron events with priority 0 for immediate cache clearing.",
        "cot_reasoning": "Step-by-step explanation of the key decisions in this code:\n1. static $done = false is the idempotency guard. This function is called from multiple code paths during plugin initialization; without the guard, hooks would be registered multiple times, triggering cache clearing multiple times per post save.\n2. Checking $GLOBALS['cache_enabled'] before registering hooks avoids adding overhead for sites where caching is explicitly disabled. If cache is off, there is no cache to clear and the hooks serve no purpose.\n3. The WPLOCKDOWN constant check prevents cache registration during maintenance mode. In lockdown, the site is intentionally serving static content and hook-triggered cache clearing would prematurely invalidate it.\n4. Priority 0 is used for post hooks rather than the default 10. Cache clearing should happen as early as possible in the action queue to prevent subsequent hooks from reading stale cache.\n5. Both wp_trash_post and before_delete_post are hooked because trashing (soft delete) and permanent deletion are separate events and both should invalidate the relevant cache entries.\n6. Comment hooks (comment_post, edit_comment) are included because new comments change the post's content visible to visitors, invalidating the cached HTML.\n7. The cron hook allows the cache to re-enable itself after a timed lockdown, supporting maintenance-window workflows.",
        "training_tags": ["static-variable-guard", "idempotent-registration", "add_action", "hook-registration", "cache-invalidation", "priority-management", "argument-count-in-hooks", "global-state-check", "defined-constant-check"],
        "complexity": "simple",
    },
    # 19: wp_insert_post
    {
        "instruction": "<wp_gen> Create the core WordPress wp_insert_post function that sanitizes all post fields, validates post author and post type, handles date parsing and normalization, fires before-insert filters, performs an INSERT or UPDATE to wp_posts using $wpdb->insert or $wpdb->update with prepared statements, updates post meta, fires post-insert action hooks including post-type-specific variants, cleans post caches, and returns the new post ID or WP_Error.",
        "cot_reasoning": "Step-by-step explanation of the key decisions in this code:\n1. $unsanitized_postarr captures the raw input before any sanitization for passing to filter hooks. Some hooks intentionally need access to the original unmodified data (e.g., for comparing with sanitized versions).\n2. wp_parse_args merges with defaults so all array keys exist downstream, eliminating repeated isset() checks throughout the function body.\n3. Post author validation checks that the author ID exists as a user. Inserting a post with a non-existent author ID would corrupt post metadata and break author archive queries.\n4. $wpdb->insert() and $wpdb->update() are used instead of $wpdb->query() with manually constructed SQL. These methods handle escaping internally via $wpdb->prepare(), preventing SQL injection even if upstream sanitization is bypassed.\n5. Multiple do_action hooks ('wp_insert_post', 'save_post', 'save_post_{$post_type}') fire to support the full hook hierarchy. Plugins may listen to the specific post type hook to avoid running on every post save.\n6. clean_post_cache($post_id) invalidates the object cache for the saved post, ensuring subsequent get_post() calls return fresh data rather than stale cached values.\n7. The $wp_error parameter controls whether the function returns false or a WP_Error object on failure. This backward-compatibility parameter allows callers written before WP_Error was available to continue working.",
        "training_tags": ["wp_insert_post", "sql:prepared_statements", "sql:targeted_select", "wpdb->insert", "wpdb->update", "do_action", "apply_filters", "clean_post_cache", "wp_error", "post-insertion", "capability-checks", "sanitization"],
        "complexity": "complex",
    },
    # 20: redirect_canonical
    {
        "instruction": "<wp_gen> Create the WordPress redirect_canonical function that detects when the requested URL should be redirected to a canonical URL, exempts POST requests, checks for valid preview nonces to avoid redirect loops, uses $wpdb->prepare for slug lookup queries to prevent SQL injection, normalizes permalink structure (trailing slash, www, index.php), and uses wp_redirect with 301 status, all wrapped behind an apply_filters hook for suppression.",
        "cot_reasoning": "Step-by-step explanation of the key decisions in this code:\n1. The REQUEST_METHOD check at the top exempts POST, PUT, DELETE requests from canonical redirects. Redirecting a form submission would discard the POST data and break form processing.\n2. Preview nonce verification is checked before any redirect logic: if a valid preview nonce is present, the function returns early. Redirecting a valid preview URL would break the WordPress post preview system.\n3. $wpdb->prepare() is used for all database queries (e.g., looking up page slugs). Even though the values come from the URL, they are user-controlled and must be parameterized to prevent SQL injection.\n4. The redirect is only performed when $do_redirect is true, allowing callers (like unit tests or plugins) to call redirect_canonical($url, false) to get the canonical URL without triggering the actual redirect.\n5. wp_redirect() with status 301 is used for permanent redirects. Browser and search engine caches remember 301 redirects, improving performance for repeat visitors and consolidating SEO link equity.\n6. The function handles multiple URL normalization cases in a single pass rather than redirecting once per issue, preventing redirect chains.\n7. apply_filters('redirect_canonical', $redirect_url, $requested_url) allows plugins to suppress the redirect (return false) or modify the destination URL — essential for i18n plugins that manage URL structures.",
        "training_tags": ["redirect_canonical", "wp_redirect", "wpdb->prepare", "sql:prepared_statements", "nonce_verification", "canonical-url", "301-redirect", "apply_filters", "REQUEST_METHOD"],
        "complexity": "complex",
    },
    # 21: contact-form-7 form_html
    {
        "instruction": "<wp_gen> Create a Contact Form 7 method that renders a contact form as HTML, supporting configurable HTML attributes (id, name, title, class), generating unique sequential form IDs for accessibility, rendering ARIA attributes (aria-label, aria-describedby) only when the corresponding values are non-empty, including a hidden spam-prevention field, firing do_action hooks for content injection before and after the form, and escaping all output attributes with esc_attr.",
        "cot_reasoning": "Step-by-step explanation of the key decisions in this code:\n1. wp_parse_args() with defaults handles both string and array $options input. Contact Form 7 shortcodes can pass attributes as either format, and wp_parse_args normalizes both to an array.\n2. A sequential counter ensures each form on the page gets a unique HTML ID. Duplicate IDs are invalid HTML and break JavaScript/CSS selectors that rely on ID uniqueness.\n3. aria-label and aria-describedby are conditionally added only when the corresponding attributes (html_title) are non-empty. Adding empty aria attributes is worse than omitting them — screen readers would read empty labels aloud.\n4. All output attributes are passed through esc_attr() before insertion into the HTML string. Form IDs, names, and classes are user-configurable via shortcode, creating a potential XSS vector if unescaped.\n5. The hidden spam-prevention field is output inside the <form> tag to work with all submission handling. Placing it outside the form would cause browsers to omit it from the submitted data.\n6. do_action() hooks before and after the form fields allow third-party integrations to inject content (honeypot fields, GDPR notices) without requiring a core plugin modification.\n7. The 'raw_form' output option bypasses all processing and returns the form template in a <pre><code> block, useful for debugging template syntax.",
        "training_tags": ["security:output_escaping", "a11y:aria_attributes", "a11y:form_labels", "i18n:translation_functions", "form-rendering", "wp_parse_args", "esc_attr", "do_action"],
        "complexity": "medium",
    },
    # 22: CF7 scan_callback
    {
        "instruction": "<wp_gen> Create a Contact Form 7 regex scan callback that processes shortcode-like form tag syntax, handles the [[tag]] double-bracket escape by stripping one layer of brackets, extracts tag type and base type (trimming the * suffix), parses attributes with a dedicated method, fires apply_filters to allow custom tag modification, and populates a scanned tag registry used during form submission validation.",
        "cot_reasoning": "Step-by-step explanation of the key decisions in this code:\n1. The double-bracket [[tag]] escape check is evaluated first. If matched, the outer brackets are stripped and the inner text returned verbatim. This must come first so the escape syntax is never processed as a real tag.\n2. trim($tag_type, '*') separates the basetype from the starred variant (e.g., 'text*' is a required text field). Storing both $tag_type and $tag_basetype allows dispatching on basetype while preserving the required-field flag.\n3. $this->parse_atts() handles attribute parsing — quoted strings, unquoted values, and boolean flags like 'required'. Delegating this to a dedicated method keeps scan_callback focused on orchestration.\n4. apply_filters('wpcf7_form_tag', ...) allows custom tag handlers to modify or replace the scanned tag data. This is the plugin's primary extension mechanism for adding new field types.\n5. The scanned tag is added to an internal registry (not just returned). This registry is consulted during form submission validation to know which fields to validate, ensuring the validation logic has access to all form tag configurations.\n6. The $replace flag controls whether the callback returns a string (for rendering) or adds to the registry (for scanning). This dual-mode design allows the same callback to serve both the scan pass and the render pass.",
        "training_tags": ["contact-form-7", "shortcode-scanning", "apply_filters", "tag-registry", "escape-syntax", "form-tag-processing", "regex-callback"],
        "complexity": "medium",
    },
    # 23: query-monitor template process
    {
        "instruction": "<wp_gen> Create a Query Monitor collector process method that resolves the active theme template file hierarchy by normalizing paths with cross-platform separator handling, applying array_unique to deduplicate the hierarchy, detecting block themes via get_block_theme_folders, resolving parent/child theme relationships by comparing stylesheet and template directories, and populating a typed data object with the final template path and theme metadata.",
        "cot_reasoning": "Step-by-step explanation of the key decisions in this code:\n1. QM_Util::standard_dir() normalizes directory separators (backslash to forward slash on Windows). WordPress's template functions return paths using the OS separator, but comparison requires a consistent format.\n2. array_unique() is applied to the template hierarchy before processing. The hierarchy can contain duplicates when multiple template tags resolve to the same file, and duplicates would produce redundant entries in the debug panel.\n3. The block theme folder detection (get_block_theme_folders()) handles the new block theme directory structure introduced in WordPress 5.9. Without this, block themes would show incorrect template paths in the debug output.\n4. Child vs. parent theme detection compares stylesheet_directory to template_directory. When they differ, a child theme is active; when equal, the theme has no parent. This determines how template inheritance is displayed.\n5. locate_template() results are stored with their full path to allow the debug panel to show which directory each template came from, crucial for diagnosing template override issues.\n6. The data object ($this->data) accumulates results rather than returning them. The collector pattern separates data collection from display, allowing the same data to be shown in multiple output formats (HTML panel, JSON API, CLI).",
        "training_tags": ["data-collection", "theme-template-hierarchy", "block-themes", "child-themes", "locate_template", "get_stylesheet_directory", "get_template_directory", "get_theme_root", "object-properties", "collector-pattern"],
        "complexity": "medium",
    },
    # 24: query-monitor QM_Collector_PHP_Errors::error_handler
    {
        "instruction": "<wp_gen> Create a custom PHP error handler for a debugging plugin that maps PHP error constants to severity level strings via switch/case, fires a do_action hook for each error, deduplicates repeated errors using MD5 hashing of message+file+line, conditionally captures backtraces based on a flag, applies wp_strip_all_tags to error messages, handles PHP 8.4 E_STRICT deprecation via version_compare, and stores classified errors in a structured data array.",
        "cot_reasoning": "Step-by-step explanation of the key decisions in this code:\n1. The switch/case on $errno maps PHP's integer error constants to human-readable level strings. This decoupling means the display layer never needs to know PHP error constant values.\n2. do_action('qm/collect/new_php_error') fires for every error, allowing external plugins to react to PHP errors without hooking into the low-level set_error_handler mechanism. This is important for error monitoring integrations.\n3. MD5 of the concatenated message+file+line is used as a deduplication key. PHP errors inside loops can fire hundreds of times for the same issue; MD5 keying collapses these into a single entry with an occurrence count.\n4. debug_backtrace() is conditionally called based on $do_trace flag. Backtraces are expensive (memory and CPU); for errors in tight loops, disabling the trace prevents out-of-memory conditions.\n5. wp_strip_all_tags() is applied to the error message before display. Some error messages contain HTML (from objects using __toString()), which would be rendered as markup in the debug panel.\n6. version_compare(PHP_VERSION, '8.4', '>=') handles the removal of E_STRICT in PHP 8.4. Without this check, the handler would attempt to classify an unknown error constant.\n7. The error_reporting() check respects the site's configured error reporting level. A handler that ignores error_reporting would display errors that the site operator has intentionally suppressed.",
        "training_tags": ["php-error-handler", "do_action", "apply_filters", "version_compare", "error-suppression", "backtrace", "wp_strip_all_tags", "deduplication-by-md5-key", "static-property-caching", "PHP8.4-compatibility", "collector-pattern"],
        "complexity": "medium",
    },
    # 25: query-monitor QM_Collector_Cache::process
    {
        "instruction": "<wp_gen> Create a Query Monitor cache statistics collector process method that checks external object cache status via wp_using_ext_object_cache, safely introspects the global $wp_object_cache object using get_object_vars and array_key_exists to avoid fatal errors on implementations without hit/miss tracking, calculates a cache hit percentage, and stores the results in the collector's typed data object.",
        "cot_reasoning": "Step-by-step explanation of the key decisions in this code:\n1. wp_using_ext_object_cache() is called rather than checking $wp_object_cache directly. This WordPress function is the documented API for determining external cache status and handles edge cases like persistent object cache adapters that set the flag via wp-config.php.\n2. is_object($wp_object_cache) guards before any property access. The global may not be set on early requests or in unit tests; a null/false check prevents fatal errors.\n3. get_object_vars() is used to read cache properties rather than direct property access ($wp_object_cache->cache_hits). Direct access would throw a fatal error if the property does not exist in the specific object cache implementation being used.\n4. array_key_exists() checks before reading from $object_vars ensure the code degrades gracefully with object cache implementations that do not track hit/miss statistics.\n5. The hit percentage is calculated as (hits / (hits + misses)) * 100, with a guard against division by zero when both are zero (fresh page with no cache activity).\n6. method_exists() checks are used before calling optional methods on the cache object. Not all cache adapters implement the same interface, so optional method detection is required.",
        "training_tags": ["global-variable-access", "object-cache-inspection", "defensive-programming", "wp_using_ext_object_cache", "data-collector-pattern", "scalar-type-checking", "cache-statistics", "get_object_vars", "method_exists-check"],
        "complexity": "simple",
    },
    # 26: query-monitor determine_callback
    {
        "instruction": "<wp_gen> Create a Query Monitor utility method that resolves a WordPress hook callback (string, array, or closure) into a structured data object containing file path, line number, function name, and component, using PHP's ReflectionFunction and ReflectionMethod APIs, handling static string methods ('Class::method'), closures, invokable objects with __invoke, and legacy create_function callbacks with WP_Error returns on failure.",
        "cot_reasoning": "Step-by-step explanation of the key decisions in this code:\n1. String callbacks containing '::' are split into [class, method] arrays before reflection. PHP's ReflectionMethod requires a class name and method name separately; the '::' static method syntax is a shorthand that must be decomposed.\n2. ReflectionMethod is used for array callbacks ([object, 'method'] or ['Class', 'method']). ReflectionMethod provides getFileName() and getStartLine() without instantiating the class, making it usable for static methods.\n3. ReflectionFunction is used for closures and plain function strings. Closures have a getFileName() and getStartLine(), allowing the debug panel to show exactly where each anonymous function was defined.\n4. WP_Error is returned (rather than thrown) for unresolvable callbacks. The caller can check for WP_Error and display a 'callback not resolvable' message rather than crashing the debug panel.\n5. create_function() callbacks (a legacy PHP construct deprecated in PHP 7.2) are specially detected and flagged. They cannot be reflected meaningfully, so a descriptive placeholder is returned rather than a ReflectionException.\n6. Invokable objects (those with __invoke()) are handled via ReflectionMethod($object, '__invoke'). This covers cases like callable class instances used as hook callbacks in OOP-heavy plugin architectures.\n7. The result object (QM_Data_Callback) uses typed properties rather than a plain array, making the data structure self-documenting and allowing IDEs to type-check consumers of this method.",
        "training_tags": ["reflection_api", "callback_introspection", "closure_detection", "ReflectionMethod", "ReflectionFunction", "WP_Error_usage", "exception_handling", "type_detection", "static_methods", "invokable_objects", "legacy_create_function_handling"],
        "complexity": "complex",
    },
    # 27: woocommerce-gateway-stripe init
    {
        "instruction": "<wp_gen> Create a WooCommerce Stripe gateway plugin init action callback that conditionally loads an admin privacy class behind is_admin(), uses file_exists before requiring optional feature flag classes, requires all payment method class files, instantiates and registers gateway classes with WooCommerce's payment_gateways filter, initializes webhook handling, and sets up express checkout (Apple Pay/Google Pay) support.",
        "cot_reasoning": "Step-by-step explanation of the key decisions in this code:\n1. is_admin() gates the privacy class loading. The WC_Stripe_Privacy class contains admin-only GDPR data exporter/eraser registration; loading it on front-end requests would waste memory and potentially trigger premature admin function calls.\n2. file_exists() wraps the feature flags require_once because this file may not be present in all build configurations (e.g., split packages or partial installs). A missing file_exists check would produce a fatal error for those configurations.\n3. All payment method class files are required here (at init priority) rather than at plugins_loaded. WooCommerce's gateway filter runs during init, so all classes must be defined before that filter fires.\n4. The 'woocommerce_payment_gateways' filter is used to register gateways rather than directly instantiating them. This is WooCommerce's documented API for gateway registration, ensuring proper lifecycle management by WooCommerce core.\n5. Webhook handling is initialized separately because webhooks are received on dedicated endpoint URLs that exist independently of the checkout flow.\n6. Express checkout initialization is conditional on gateway availability and SSL status (checked inside the express checkout helper), following a defense-in-depth approach rather than checking only at display time.",
        "training_tags": ["plugin-initialization", "is_admin-gating", "file_exists-guard", "add_filter", "woocommerce-extension", "payment-gateway", "require_once", "feature-flags"],
        "complexity": "complex",
    },
    # 28: process_checkout_session
    {
        "instruction": "<wp_gen> Create a WooCommerce Stripe webhook handler method for checkout.session.completed events that refreshes a database cache with webhook payload data, maps the Stripe session to a WooCommerce order via stored meta, validates idempotency by checking if the order is already paid, validates payment intent status, saves payment metadata on the order before calling payment_complete, and logs all error conditions without rethrowing to ensure a 200 OK webhook response.",
        "cot_reasoning": "Step-by-step explanation of the key decisions in this code:\n1. The database cache is refreshed at the start of the handler with the webhook payload data. Webhooks may arrive after the checkout page has cached a partial session object; refreshing ensures all subsequent reads reflect the final payment state.\n2. Order lookup uses custom post meta (the Stripe session ID stored on the order) rather than an order ID embedded in the webhook. The Stripe checkout.session object contains the metadata set when the session was created, making it the reliable link back to the WooCommerce order.\n3. The already-processed check (is_order_paid_or_cancelled()) provides idempotency — webhooks can be delivered multiple times by Stripe, so the handler must be safe to re-run on a previously completed order.\n4. Payment intent status validation ensures the handler only completes orders for successful payment intents. A checkout session can be created without payment (e.g., $0 orders), so the payment_intent field may be null.\n5. Order meta is saved (Stripe charge ID, payment intent ID) before calling payment_complete(). payment_complete() triggers email notifications; the meta must be present before emails are sent so recipients see complete information.\n6. All error cases log via WC_Stripe_Logger::log() rather than triggering exceptions. Webhook handlers must return a 200 OK response to prevent Stripe from retrying; logging errors without rethrowing achieves this.",
        "training_tags": ["webhook-handler", "woocommerce", "stripe", "payment-processing", "idempotency", "order-meta", "payment_complete", "cache-refresh", "error-logging"],
        "complexity": "complex",
    },
